WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.200
What do you get when hot and cool join forces?

00:00:03.200 --> 00:00:04.700
Hot eats!

00:00:04.700 --> 00:00:06.200
Cool treats!

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:11.090
You want it all, it's all here at Dairy Queen.

00:00:11.090 --> 00:00:12.090
It's hot!

00:00:12.090 --> 00:00:15.090
All kinds of burgers, hot dogs, chicken and fish sandwiches.

00:00:15.090 --> 00:00:16.090
It's cool!

00:00:16.090 --> 00:00:20.090
Plus all kinds of soft-serve and yogurt treats you can't get anywhere else.

00:00:20.090 --> 00:00:23.090
It's the one place to be when you want more than one thing to eat.

00:00:23.090 --> 00:00:28.090
Come to Dairy Queen at these convenient locations in Hasbro Heights, Haskell, Oakland, Paramus and Ringwood.

00:00:28.090 --> 00:00:33.970
Jesus Horus Rex knows it's out there!

00:00:34.170 --> 00:00:36.170
Somewhere in the vicinity of Kraft Macaroni and Cheese.

00:00:36.170 --> 00:00:37.170
To the left.

00:00:37.170 --> 00:00:39.170
No, the right of Kraft Singles.

00:00:39.170 --> 00:00:42.170
In fact, of all those packs of handy-snacks, it's Herbert Mogenberg!

00:00:42.170 --> 00:00:44.170
No, it's the Kraft Treasure Trunk!

00:00:44.170 --> 00:00:46.170
Yes, the Kraft Treasure Trunk!

00:00:46.170 --> 00:00:49.170
There's fabulous dolls, monstrous trunks and more!

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:52.170
You can get details and treasure points on Kraft Singles.

00:00:52.170 --> 00:00:54.170
Handysnacks are Kraft Macaroni and Cheese.

00:00:54.170 --> 00:01:00.170
So put on your thinking caps, plan your attack, because the Kraft Treasure Trunk is out there!

00:01:00.170 --> 00:01:03.170
Making Barbie clothes is fun to do!

00:01:03.370 --> 00:01:08.370
With tie and dye, I'll make the hottest styles, color swirls in wild designs.

00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:10.370
Look what I made!

00:01:10.370 --> 00:01:11.370
That's cool!

00:01:11.370 --> 00:01:14.370
And with my fashion decorator, I can make her clothes really fine.

00:01:14.370 --> 00:01:15.370
Cool!

00:01:15.370 --> 00:01:17.370
I'll put on stars, it's what I like.

00:01:17.370 --> 00:01:20.370
Now Barbie looks too spied!

00:01:20.370 --> 00:01:23.370
Making Barbie clothes is fun to do!

00:01:23.370 --> 00:01:25.370
Making Barbie clothes is fun to do!

00:01:25.370 --> 00:01:28.370
Barbie tie and dye fashion and fashion decorator sold separately.

00:01:28.370 --> 00:01:31.370
Dolls and batteries not included, dye dries overnight.

00:01:31.370 --> 00:01:35.370
When it comes to great taste in Ego Waffles, nobody likes them more than Dan Marley.

00:01:35.370 --> 00:01:39.370
Except maybe his long time rival, B.J. Armstrong.

00:01:40.370 --> 00:01:43.370
Dan knows B.J. loves that gold in Ego Christmas.

00:01:43.370 --> 00:01:46.370
B.J. knows Dan loves that delicious Ego taste.

00:01:46.370 --> 00:01:48.370
Only thing they didn't know was...

00:01:49.370 --> 00:01:51.370
How much Marty Dawson loves him?

00:01:51.370 --> 00:01:52.370
Hey!

00:01:52.370 --> 00:01:54.370
Say I go my Ego!

00:01:54.370 --> 00:01:58.370
Ego Waffles, the part of a good breakfast that's just too much fun to let go.

00:01:58.370 --> 00:02:02.060
Look, you hear this?

00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:04.060
Time has come.

00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:07.060
The big orange couch is in place.

00:02:07.060 --> 00:02:09.060
So hop on!

00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:34.950
And tonight, Nick Snicks with your hosts, Pete and Pete.

00:02:34.950 --> 00:02:36.950
Hi, I'm Pete. This is my brother, Pete.

00:02:36.950 --> 00:02:40.950
And we were wondering, since Clarissa is so good at explaining things,

00:02:40.950 --> 00:02:44.950
maybe she could help us solve one of life's greatest mysteries.

00:02:44.950 --> 00:02:47.950
How many pounds are there in a bucket?

00:02:47.950 --> 00:02:54.390
Let the snicking begin as Clarissa explains it all next on Snick.

00:02:54.390 --> 00:03:06.230
I almost have enough of these cereal box tops saved up to get a...

00:03:06.230 --> 00:03:09.230
genuine plastic cow mug.

00:03:09.230 --> 00:03:13.230
Just another 13,000 of these and I can trade them in for something I actually want.

00:03:13.230 --> 00:03:16.230
As the illustrious wordsmith Samuel Johnson once said,

00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:19.230
Or was it the guy in the white suit on Fantasy Island?

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:22.230
Life is a progress from want to want.

00:03:22.230 --> 00:03:27.230
Personally, I think this whole idea of wanting stuff can be categorized into your four basic want groups.

00:03:27.230 --> 00:03:31.230
Okay, number one, wanting something you know you'll never get.

00:03:31.230 --> 00:03:48.500
And the brand new car goes to lucky-winning ticket number 5281990.

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:54.660
And there's basic want number two.

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:57.660
Watching something you only think you want until you get it.

00:03:57.660 --> 00:04:01.660
Like the time I just had to have one of those twisty curls.

00:04:01.660 --> 00:04:09.460
Insert hair section A through loop B and presto.

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:16.200
Next, basic want number three.

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:19.200
Wanting something you never, ever, ever thought you'd want.

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:22.540
Voila!

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:26.540
Escagot du Dali.

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:30.860
Escagot? Yuck.

00:04:30.860 --> 00:04:35.860
Like the time Dad took a French cooking class and made us all eat his final exam.

00:04:35.860 --> 00:04:43.780
Moi? Who'da thunk?

00:04:43.780 --> 00:04:49.140
But finally we come to that rarest basic want group of all.

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:53.140
Wanting something you've always wanted and actually getting it.

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:56.140
Well, today I'm getting a taste of basic want group number four

00:04:56.140 --> 00:04:59.140
and I didn't even have to save zero box tops for it

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:04.670
because I've just landed my dream job.

00:05:04.670 --> 00:05:07.670
Clarissa Darling, editor in chief.

00:05:07.670 --> 00:05:11.670
Watch out everybody, the school newspaper is in my hands.

00:05:11.670 --> 00:06:07.190
Now here is something we can use.

00:06:07.190 --> 00:06:09.190
An espresso maker for the car?

00:06:09.190 --> 00:06:11.190
Yeah, plugs right into the cigarette lighter.

00:06:11.190 --> 00:06:14.190
That way you never have to worry about falling asleep at the wheel again.

00:06:14.190 --> 00:06:16.190
I don't think so, Marshall.

00:06:16.190 --> 00:06:19.190
Whoa, whoa, whoa, look at this, look at this, huh?

00:06:19.190 --> 00:06:22.190
A portable, waterproof chest set.

00:06:22.190 --> 00:06:24.190
It's for the pool? Yeah.

00:06:24.190 --> 00:06:26.190
We don't have a pool?

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:28.190
I could use it in the bathtub.

00:06:28.190 --> 00:06:33.500
You always take showers. Oh, right, right.

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:35.500
Oh, Clarissa, congratulations.

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:37.500
Yeah, sport, this is really exciting.

00:06:37.500 --> 00:06:40.500
Thanks, I know, but how do you know? I was just gonna tell you.

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:43.500
Ah, news travels fast. Your journalism advisor called.

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:45.500
Mr. McGuffey.

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:47.500
He said that you're the youngest editor of the school paper ever.

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:49.500
That is quite an honor.

00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:52.500
When I was in high school, I edited a paper myself.

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:54.500
I don't remember that. Oh, yeah.

00:06:54.500 --> 00:06:57.500
Kind of an underground thing called Dig This.

00:06:57.500 --> 00:07:00.500
My buddy Eric and I, we thought it uproaded, edited ourselves.

00:07:00.500 --> 00:07:03.500
Just never got around to typing it.

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:05.500
Very underground.

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:08.500
The Thomas Tupper Times is definitely above ground.

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:10.500
I want to make the next issue the best ever.

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:13.500
You know, I'd be happy to help you with the design elements.

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:15.500
I see a whole new look for you, sport.

00:07:15.500 --> 00:07:17.500
More color, a slicker logo.

00:07:17.500 --> 00:07:19.500
I think I'll go work up a few ideas.

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:21.500
Dad, you really don't have to do that.

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:23.500
No, no, don't be silly. I'd love to be of help.

00:07:23.500 --> 00:07:26.500
Just think, you know, watching you following in the footsteps of

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:29.500
Johann Gutenberg and Ben Franklin and Rupert Murdoch.

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:31.500
He can get carried away.

00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:33.500
Let me know if I can do anything.

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:37.060
Thanks, Mom.

00:07:37.060 --> 00:07:38.060
Hiya, Chief.

00:07:38.060 --> 00:07:39.060
Chief?

00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:42.060
I need to talk about my next assignment, Chief.

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:44.060
I'm gonna need a lot more space for this one.

00:07:44.060 --> 00:07:47.060
Oh, let's say about 10,000 words.

00:07:47.060 --> 00:07:51.060
And, uh, I think at this point a portrait above my byline would be appropriate.

00:07:51.060 --> 00:07:52.060
You mean a warning label.

00:07:52.060 --> 00:07:54.060
I'm gonna help you put this paper on the map.

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:57.060
Look, Ferguson, I know you've been reviewing movies for the paper.

00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:00.060
Uh, I prefer to think of them as films.

00:08:00.060 --> 00:08:03.060
And I don't review by critique.

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:08.060
Okay, okay, I hate to admit it, but your writing is pretty good.

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:11.060
Pretty good? It's pre-pulitzer.

00:08:11.060 --> 00:08:13.060
Yeah, very pre-pulitzer.

00:08:13.060 --> 00:08:16.060
Well, lucky for you, I'm not hiring on the basis of personality.

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:18.060
Just don't bug me.

00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:23.060
Speaking of bugs, I plan to give complete coverage of an important cultural event.

00:08:23.060 --> 00:08:27.060
Giant insects and mutant chillers.

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:30.060
A retrospective of the films of Turner B. Gerhardt.

00:08:30.060 --> 00:08:31.060
Who?

00:08:31.060 --> 00:08:33.060
Only the king of catastrophe, Carnage and Cleavage.

00:08:33.060 --> 00:08:36.060
Plus, I'll get press passes to all my favorite flicks.

00:08:36.060 --> 00:08:39.060
I guess bad movies do have their appeal.

00:08:39.060 --> 00:08:43.060
Okay, it sounds amusing, but you're not getting any more space than usual.

00:08:43.060 --> 00:08:49.010
Washington Post, the New York Times, the Hack and Sack Herald.

00:08:49.010 --> 00:08:51.010
You know what'd be great?

00:08:51.010 --> 00:08:53.010
Ink that doesn't come off on your hands.

00:08:53.010 --> 00:08:55.010
I mean, great paper should leave their mark.

00:08:55.010 --> 00:08:57.010
This is ridiculous.

00:08:57.010 --> 00:08:59.010
In the meantime, I guess these'll do.

00:08:59.010 --> 00:09:01.010
Well, so much for research.

00:09:01.010 --> 00:09:04.010
Now I just have to get through this slush pile.

00:09:04.010 --> 00:09:07.010
All these submissions, suddenly everyone I know is a writer.

00:09:07.010 --> 00:09:10.540
Hi, Sam.

00:09:10.540 --> 00:09:16.330
Hey, Clarissa. Working on the paper?

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:18.330
Yeah, I've been looking for ideas.

00:09:18.330 --> 00:09:20.330
So what'd you think of mine?

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:22.330
You submitted an idea.

00:09:22.330 --> 00:09:24.330
Yeah, you're gonna love it.

00:09:24.330 --> 00:09:25.330
Tell it to me, Sam.

00:09:25.330 --> 00:09:27.330
Music reviews.

00:09:27.330 --> 00:09:30.330
Music reviews? What's so new about music reviews?

00:09:30.330 --> 00:09:33.330
Alternative music, music reviews.

00:09:33.330 --> 00:09:36.330
Alternative music is a way to make the paper cutting edge.

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:38.330
I like it. Thanks, Sam. I'll put it on my list.

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:40.330
Wait, that's not the whole idea.

00:09:40.330 --> 00:09:41.330
Well, what's the rest?

00:09:41.330 --> 00:09:42.330
Me.

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:43.330
You?

00:09:43.330 --> 00:09:45.330
I'll write the reviews.

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:46.330
You will?

00:09:46.330 --> 00:09:49.330
I love those groups. I feel that sound.

00:09:49.330 --> 00:09:51.330
I know you have a great ear, Sam,

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:53.330
but I didn't know you really wanted to write.

00:09:53.330 --> 00:09:55.330
I don't, but I could.

00:09:55.330 --> 00:09:57.330
With you as my editor, it'll be fun.

00:09:57.330 --> 00:10:00.330
Sam, it might not be fun. It might be hard work.

00:10:00.330 --> 00:10:02.330
Clarissa, my dad's a sports writer, remember?

00:10:02.330 --> 00:10:04.330
Journalism isn't my blood.

00:10:04.330 --> 00:10:08.330
Well, you know, I'm gonna have to be totally objective on everyone's work.

00:10:08.330 --> 00:10:09.330
Absolutely.

00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:11.330
And you can't get extensions on deadlines

00:10:11.330 --> 00:10:13.330
like in Mrs. Stilwappel's class.

00:10:13.330 --> 00:10:15.330
Of course not. A true journalist thrives on deadlines.

00:10:15.330 --> 00:10:17.330
Well, then...

00:10:17.330 --> 00:10:19.330
Okay, we'll give it a shot.

00:10:19.330 --> 00:10:21.330
Excellent.

00:10:21.330 --> 00:10:25.330
Oh, and would you mind putting my byline in four-inch caps?

00:10:25.330 --> 00:10:26.330
Sam.

00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:30.850
Just kidding.

00:10:30.850 --> 00:10:33.850
Why is it starting to seem like being a responsible journalist

00:10:33.850 --> 00:10:36.850
means being responsible for finding work for everyone I know?

00:10:36.850 --> 00:10:41.600
Hi, Clarissa.

00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:48.720
Hi, Dad.

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:50.720
Do you have a rough day at the office, Port?

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:54.720
If you mean rough, as in grueling, annoying, absolutely exhausting.

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:55.720
Yes.

00:10:55.720 --> 00:10:57.720
Well, you're the boss.

00:10:57.720 --> 00:10:59.720
Yeah, well, being the boss isn't all it's cracked up to be.

00:10:59.720 --> 00:11:01.720
Well, Clarissa, you're just gonna have to get tough, that's all.

00:11:01.720 --> 00:11:04.720
I mean, people who respect a boss who's decisive, who's demanding,

00:11:04.720 --> 00:11:08.720
you know, who's willing to lay down the law will know that I do.

00:11:08.720 --> 00:11:10.720
But you don't have a boss.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:12.720
Of course I do. Me.

00:11:12.720 --> 00:11:14.720
You know, if I'm not hard on myself, who will be?

00:11:14.720 --> 00:11:17.720
Oh, Marshall, you told me to tell you to get back to work at Quarter Pass.

00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:19.720
So get back to work.

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:22.720
All right, thanks.

00:11:22.720 --> 00:11:29.620
You think the boss has to be tough and demanding?

00:11:29.620 --> 00:11:34.620
Well, as long as she's also open-minded and willing to listen.

00:11:34.620 --> 00:11:36.620
That sounds good.

00:11:36.620 --> 00:11:39.620
It's just weird to have to say no to people I know.

00:11:39.620 --> 00:11:43.220
Of course saying no to some people is easy.

00:11:43.220 --> 00:11:44.220
Clarissa?

00:11:44.220 --> 00:11:45.220
No.

00:11:45.220 --> 00:11:47.220
I haven't even asked yet.

00:11:47.220 --> 00:11:49.220
You've been asking all day, all night, all over the place,

00:11:49.220 --> 00:11:51.220
and the answer is still no.

00:11:51.220 --> 00:11:54.220
No to your own private editorial page, no to your own private office,

00:11:54.220 --> 00:11:58.220
no to a self-interview with hot young film critic Ferguson W. Dirling.

00:11:58.220 --> 00:12:00.220
Pressure getting to you, sis?

00:12:00.220 --> 00:12:02.220
No, just you.

00:12:02.220 --> 00:12:06.220
Actually, I had in mind an interview with one of the cinema's greatest greats.

00:12:06.220 --> 00:12:09.220
I happened to have an in with a film legend.

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:12.220
Really? Scorsese, Spielberg, Fellini?

00:12:12.220 --> 00:12:14.220
Mm-hmm, even better.

00:12:14.220 --> 00:12:17.220
I managed to get access to Turner B. Gerhard.

00:12:17.220 --> 00:12:20.220
And let me tell you, the man has a lot to say about mutant cheerleaders

00:12:20.220 --> 00:12:22.220
and giant insects.

00:12:22.220 --> 00:12:25.220
Since when did the king of splatter become a film legend?

00:12:25.220 --> 00:12:30.220
Since I, Ferguson W. Dirling, film aficionado extraordinaire,

00:12:30.220 --> 00:12:32.220
decided to make him one.

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:35.220
I promise you, chief, my piece will be groundbreaking.

00:12:35.220 --> 00:12:40.220
Yeah, well, I'm gonna break something else if you don't stop calling me chief.

00:12:40.220 --> 00:12:48.460
I'll get it.

00:12:48.460 --> 00:12:50.460
Uh, pizza for Clarissa, darling?

00:12:50.460 --> 00:12:52.460
Sorry, I didn't order a pizza.

00:12:52.460 --> 00:12:56.460
Congratulations to our neighborhood school's newest editor-in-chief.

00:12:56.460 --> 00:12:59.460
I haven't tried Pat's pizza. You're in for a feast.

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:02.460
So go ahead and give this free pizza a chew.

00:13:02.460 --> 00:13:05.460
There's more from where that came from once you give us a review.

00:13:05.460 --> 00:13:08.460
Give me a bread. Tell Pat I don't accept free food.

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:10.460
Buddy's welcome to buy it, Ed.

00:13:10.460 --> 00:13:21.910
Wait. Thanks anyway.

00:13:21.910 --> 00:13:23.910
I know temptation is the root of bad bosses,

00:13:23.910 --> 00:13:27.910
but do they have to throw pizza with extra cheese and pepperoni into the equation?

00:13:27.910 --> 00:13:34.020
Those tough decisions keep getting tougher.

00:13:34.020 --> 00:13:39.020
Okay, I've read through Sam's review once, twice, three times you were out,

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:42.020
and it's really, well, not good.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:46.020
I mean, it's not just the bad grammar, the incorrect punctuation, the awkward syntax.

00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:48.020
I mean, I guess I could correct all that,

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:52.020
but it's riddled with cliches as the cliche goes.

00:13:52.020 --> 00:13:56.020
Now, here's a music review by one Leonard K. Adnoyd.

00:13:56.020 --> 00:13:59.020
It's clear, it's sharp, and Lenny is the biggest, not to mention,

00:13:59.020 --> 00:14:01.020
most boring jerk around.

00:14:01.020 --> 00:14:05.020
I guess some people talk better than they write, and some people write better than they talk.

00:14:05.020 --> 00:14:07.020
So I've got to figure out a way to talk to Sam.

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:08.020
I mean, what am I supposed to do?

00:14:08.020 --> 00:14:10.020
Buy her my best friend?

00:14:10.020 --> 00:14:13.260
Sam, hi.

00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:18.240
Hi, Clarissa.

00:14:18.240 --> 00:14:20.240
So?

00:14:20.240 --> 00:14:22.240
So, buttons.

00:14:22.240 --> 00:14:23.240
So what'd you think?

00:14:23.240 --> 00:14:24.240
Think?

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:26.240
Of my review.

00:14:26.240 --> 00:14:30.240
I really tried to capture the sound of the smashing pumpkins.

00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:32.240
Oh, yeah, I can tell.

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:35.240
I want the reader to hear the music through my words.

00:14:35.240 --> 00:14:39.240
X-R-N-M-M-N-A-H?

00:14:39.240 --> 00:14:41.240
Xenorama!

00:14:41.240 --> 00:14:43.240
Cool, huh?

00:14:43.240 --> 00:14:46.240
I think that word really gives you a feel for the lyrics and the guitar rest.

00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:48.240
Must've been rough on your computer spell check.

00:14:48.240 --> 00:14:51.240
So what'd you think about the lead?

00:14:51.240 --> 00:14:56.240
Uh, the sound of silence cannot compare to the sound of the smashing pumpkins,

00:14:56.240 --> 00:14:58.240
which is anything but silent.

00:14:58.240 --> 00:15:00.240
In fact, it's not silent at all.

00:15:00.240 --> 00:15:04.240
It's loud, and I turned it way up to bring this review to you fellow listeners

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:06.240
or, in this case, readers.

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:08.240
Does it grab you?

